\subtree{\title{Fabrication roadmap}
\taxon{protocol}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Week 1:} Print ShitBCI headframe v0.1 in PETG. Validate all 16 electrode positions against the Ultracortex 10-20 montage (cyton-dongle skill: Fp1/Fp2/C3/C4/P7/P8/O1/O2 main + F7/F8/F3/F4/T7/T8/P3/P4 Daisy). Full build volume allows single-piece print. Verify electrode unit snap-fit tolerances.}
\li{\strong{Week 2:} Print TPU 90A electrode gaskets and comfort liners. Fit-test with Cyton board + dry comb electrodes (\ref{bcf-0006}). Stream 16-channel data via dongle and measure impedance quality per cyton-dongle thresholds: target CLEAN (< 50 uV std) on all channels. Compare gasket vs. bare electrode contact impedance delta.}
\li{\strong{Week 3:} Multi-material print -- PETG frame + TPU gaskets + PVA supports in single job. Validate snap-fit tolerances for electrode units. Run sheaf-cohomology-bci consistency check: verify Tr(L_F) < 1.0 across all 16 channels during head movement (subject turns head left/right/nod while recording alpha band power).}
\li{\strong{Week 4:} Print Uncut Gem magnetometer enclosure (\ref{bcf-0031}) in ABS with integrated alignment features for 520 nm laser, BPW34 photodiode, and red gel filter. Print PLUX fNIRS sensor housings for biosignalsplux optodes. Print RF-shielded inner chamber for Cyton board in CF-PETG.}
\li{\strong{Week 5:} Print colored operad physical isolation stack -- nested enclosures matching RED/YELLOW/GREEN/BLUE security boundaries. Test EMI isolation between Cyton SPI bus (ADS1299 DRDY at 250 Hz) and ESP32 WiFi TX (2.4 GHz) using oscilloscope (\ref{bcf-0035}).}
\li{\strong{Ongoing:} Iterate headset geometry based on EEG signal quality data. Each iteration is a 4--6 hour print-to-test cycle. Accumulate design knowledge for eventual injection mold tooling. GF(3) conservation: each design iteration preserves the trit balance of the physical enclosure stack.}
}
}

\subtree{\title{Why not a cheaper printer}
\taxon{remark}
\p{The existing on-site FDM printer (\ref{bcf-0006}) lacks:}
\ul{
\li{\strong{Heated chamber} -- ABS/ASA/PA prints warp, making enclosures dimensionally unreliable. The Uncut Gem enclosure requires sub-0.5mm tolerance on laser/photodiode alignment features.}
\li{\strong{Multi-material capability} -- rigid + flexible in one print is impossible. Every BCI headset iteration requires separate prints + manual assembly + adhesive bonding, introducing failure points at electrode contact positions.}
\li{\strong{TPU reliability} -- Bowden-tube extruders jam on shore 85A--90A filaments. The H2C's direct-drive right hotend with AMS HT bypass is specifically engineered for reliable flexible filament feeding.}
\li{\strong{Build volume} -- full headframes require splitting and bonding, introducing mechanical weak points at exactly the locations where electrode pressure matters most for the ADS1299 front-end's 24-bit resolution.}
}
\p{The H2C is the critical path for ShitBCI prototyping before Mr. Ziegel commits to injection mold tooling. It is also the fabrication backbone for every physical enclosure in the horse inventory: Cyton housings, Daisy shield covers, fNIRS optode mounts, and Uncut Gem magnetometer casings.}
}
